<i>Fyffes </i>and <i>Irish Independent</i>, press article, ‘Fyffes maintient son objectif’, 27 April 2010<br/>
<a href="http://www.fructidor.fr/article/fyffes-maintient-son-objectif--8487.aspx" target="_self">http://www.fructidor.fr/article/fyffes-maintient-son-objectif-8487.aspx</a></p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>The EC communication is simply the first stage of the aid mobilisation and deployment process, and funding is likely to be made available on an annual basis from 2011. It should be noted that major problems of aid commitment and disbursement have been reported under previous banana support programmes, with funds in many instances being used for conventional development projects (e.g. road building) rather than for activities specific to the banana sector. Farmers’ leaders in the Caribbean have expressed concern at the neglect of direct assistance to farmers within EU programmes, viewing this as inconsistent with the EU’s own internal practice, where restructuring support is increasingly focused on supporting and strengthening farmers’ organisations.</p><p>Developments in the UK market highlight the volatility of banana prices and raise issues related to the distribution of value along the banana supply chain. In the context of an accelerating process of erosion of banana sector tariff preferences, ongoing competition authority investigations into the operations of major multinational banana traders and the growing commercial power of supermarkets, closer ACP-EU collaboration in examining the functioning of ACP-EU banana supply chain would appear to be appropriate. As in the EU dairy sector, this collaboration could review such issues as the distribution of commercial power along banana supply chains, the process of price formation, and the distribution of revenues along fair-trade banana supply chains.</p>
		</div>
		
